Comparison between rooms¶

In [13]:
# Crea un plot per confrontare tutte le stanze
plt.plot(white_room_data['Time'], white_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='White Room', color='black')
plt.plot(green_room_data['Time'], green_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Green Room', color='green')
plt.plot(blue_room_data['Time'], blue_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Blue Room', color='blue')
plt.plot(orange_room_data['Time'], orange_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Orange Room', color='orange')
plt.plot(red_room_data['Time'], red_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Red Room', color='red')

plt.title('Room Statistics Comparison')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('WaitingTime')
plt.grid(True)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Looking at the graph, we can come to the following considerations.

The White room shows a decreasing trend (in the first section) and then has variable peaks. Therefore, during the simulation of 09/10, an increase in demand was visible in the second half of the simulation period.

The Green room has a fairly stable waiting time, with some peaks, but which remains constant for medium-low values. Therefore, it is possible to conclude that the workload was managed efficiently.

The Blue room has fairly stable waiting times, so it was not possible to observe an overload of resources.

The Orange room has low and stable waiting times. There are no different fluctuations, so this is less used but certainly very efficient.

The Red room shows an initial decreasing trend up to a certain point, and then has variable peaks and a rise towards the end of the period. This could indicate an increase in demand in the second half of the simulation period.

All this data was collected knowing the following information about resources:

  • the nurses specialized for the white room are 4
  • the nurses who take care of the patients in the green room are 3
  • the nurses who manage the patients in the blue room are 2

Resource overload analysis.¶

In our emergency room scenario, this means looking at when rooms or resources (such as nurses, equipment, or rooms themselves) are overused or can't keep up with demand.

Peak utilization assessment¶

We can analyze peak utilization of a resource by looking at times when values ​​(e.g., usage or treatment times) are higher than average or exceed a certain threshold.

We then need to

  1. Calculate the average usage time for each room and see if there are times when the times are significantly higher than average.
  2. Display the peaks with a graph to visually identify periods when the resource is overloaded:
White Room¶
In [24]:
mean_time_white = df[df['Room'] == 'White']['WaitingTime'].mean()

# Trova le occorrenze in cui il valore supera una soglia, ad esempio 1.5 volte la media
high_usage_white = df[(df['Room'] == 'White') & (df['WaitingTime'] > 1.5 * mean_time_white)]

Identifying overloaded rooms¶

We can identify which rooms are more frequently overloaded than others by comparing the total usage time or the number of overload peaks.

The steps to follow are:

  1. Calculate the total usage time for each room and see which resource was used the most.
  2. Calculate the frequency of overloads: count how many times each room exceeded an overload threshold (for example, 1.5 times the average):
In [35]:
total_usage_per_room = df.groupby('Room')['WaitingTime'].sum()
print(total_usage_per_room)

Room
Blue      498.060309
Green     473.066333
Orange     87.892165
Red       244.033931
White     159.730256
Name: WaitingTime, dtype: float64
In [36]:
def count_overloads(room_name, threshold_factor):
    mean_time = df[df['Room'] == room_name]['WaitingTime'].mean()
    overloads = df[(df['Room'] == room_name) & (df['WaitingTime'] > threshold_factor * mean_time)]
    return len(overloads)

overload_counts = {room: count_overloads(room, 1.5) for room in df['Room'].unique()}
print(overload_counts)

{'White': 1, 'Green': 4, 'Blue': 0, 'Orange': 1, 'Red': 1}

Comparison of rooms over time:¶

In this section we report a graph that compares the resource usage over time between different rooms can help you identify which rooms are most often overloaded.

In [37]:
threshold_value = df['WaitingTime'].mean() * 1.5
In [38]:
plt.plot(white_room_data['Time'], white_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='White Room', color='gray')
plt.plot(green_room_data['Time'], green_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Green Room', color='green')
plt.plot(blue_room_data['Time'], blue_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Blue Room', color='blue')
plt.plot(orange_room_data['Time'], orange_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Orange Room', color='orange')
plt.plot(red_room_data['Time'], red_room_data['WaitingTime'], label='Red Room', color='red')
plt.axhline(y=threshold_value, color='purple', linestyle='--', label='Overload Threshold')
plt.title('Resource Utilization Over Time')
plt.xlabel('Time')
plt.ylabel('Value')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In the graph, we clearly see that:

  • Overload in the White and Red Rooms: These rooms frequently exceed the overload threshold, suggesting the need for additional resources or reprioritization.
  • Good management in the Green and Blue Rooms: These rooms show stable utilization and do not appear to suffer from significant overloads.
  • Underutilized Orange Room: The Orange Room may have too many resources dedicated compared to the actual demand, which may indicate wasted capacity.

Percentage of patients treated within an acceptable time¶

This KPI measures the percentage of patients treated within an acceptable time.

To measure this, you need to filter out the patients coded orange and calculate how many are treated within the time limit (for example, one h for the Green Codeour).

In [39]:
white_treated = white_room_data[white_room_data['WaitingTime'] <= 36].shape[0]
total_white_patients = white_room_data.shape[0]

green_treated = green_room_data[green_room_data['WaitingTime'] <= 16].shape[0]
total_green_patients = green_room_data.shape[0]

blue_treated = blue_room_data[blue_room_data['WaitingTime'] <= 12].shape[0]
total_blue_patients = blue_room_data.shape[0]

orange_treated = orange_room_data[orange_room_data['WaitingTime'] <= 4].shape[0]
total_orange_patients = orange_room_data.shape[0]
In [40]:
percentage_white_treated = (white_treated / total_white_patients) * 100
print(f'Percentage of White Room patients treated within 36 minutes: {percentage_white_treated}%')

percentage_green_treated = (green_treated / total_green_patients) * 100
print(f'Percentage of Green Room patients treated within 16 minutes: {percentage_green_treated}%')

percentage_blue_treated = (blue_treated / total_blue_patients) * 100
print(f'Percentage of Blue Room patients treated within 12 minutes: {percentage_green_treated}%')

percentage_blue_treated = (orange_treated / total_orange_patients) * 100
print(f'Percentage of Orange Room patients treated within 4 minutes: {percentage_green_treated}%')

The duration of the treatment was chosen by observing the data entered in the simulation: if the maximum management time was 40, we want to observe the percentage of patients managed in 80% of the time.
